    <id>http://deshipu.art/projects/project-180472/</id>
    <title>Home Button for Keyboards</title>
    <updated>2021-06-22T00:00:00+02:00</updated>
    <content type="html">&lt;section id="home-button-for-keyboards"&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Use phone’s trackpad as a pointing device.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="project-thumb"&gt;
&lt;a class="reference external image-reference" href="/_images/2246631624364847469.jpg"&gt;&lt;img alt="projects/project-180472/images/2246631624364847469.jpg" src="projects/project-180472/images/2246631624364847469.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight-none notranslate"&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;It&amp;#39;s a common practice in custom keyboards to include some kind of a
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;pointing device on them, so that we can move the mouse cursor without
having to take the hands off the home row. A variety of devices are
used: analog joysticks, thinkpad trackpoints, small trackballs. But
some phones have a device that would be ideal for this: the “home”
button with a built-in optical trackpad.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unfortunately, even though you can easily get those buttons as
replacement parts, nobody seems to be using them — and that is
probably because there seems to be very little documentation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I decided to try and reverse-engineer one particular model of such a
